06715nam a22010335i 9780823280056DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232800567 a10.1515/97808232800562doi  a(DE-B1597)555288  a(OCoLC)1017001321  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPSY0260002bisacsh04a150.19/5222300aFreud and Monotheism :bMoses and the Violent Origins of Religion /ced. by Gilad Sharvit, Karen S. Feldman. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBerkeley Forum in the Humanities00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. “Why [the Jews] Have Attracted This Undying Hatred” -- t2. Geistigkeit: A Problematic Concept -- t3. Heine and Freud: Deferred Action and the Concept of History -- t4. Freud’s Moses: Murder, Exile, and the Question of Belonging -- t5. A Leap of Faith into Moses: Freud’s Invitation to Evenly Suspended Attention -- t6. Freud, Sellin, and the Murder of Moses -- t7. Creating the Jews: Mosaic Discourse in Freud and Hosea -- t8. Is Psychic Phylogenesis Only a Phantasy? New Biological Developments in Trauma Inheritance -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the last few decades, vibrant debates regarding post-secularism have found inspiration and provocation in the works of Sigmund Freud. A new interest in the interconnection of psychoanalysis, religion and political theory has emerged, allowing Freud’s illuminating examination of the religious and mystical practices in “Obsessive Neurosis and Religious Practices,” and the exegesis of the origins of ethics in religion in Totem and Taboo, to gain currency in recent debates on modernity. In that context, the pivotal role of Freud’s masterpiece, Moses and Monotheism, is widely recognized. Freud and Monotheism brings together fundamental new contributions to discourses on Freud and Moses, as well as new research at the intersections of theology, political theory, and history in Freud’s psychoanalytic work. Highlighting the broad impact of Moses and Monotheism across the humanities, the contributors hail from such diverse disciplines as philosophy, comparative literature, cultural studies, German studies, Jewish studies and psychoanalysis.Jan Assmann and Richard Bernstein, whose books pioneered the earlier debate that initiated the Freud and Moses discourse, seize the opportunity to revisit and revise their groundbreaking work. Gabriele Schwab, Gilad Sharvit, Karen Feldman, and Yael Segalovitz engage with the idiosyncratic, eccentric and fertile nature of the book as a Spӓtstil, and explore radical interpretations of Freud’s literary practice, theory of religion and therapeutic practice. Ronald Hendel offers an alternative history for the Mosaic discourse within the biblical text, Catherine Malabou reconnects Freud’s theory of psychic phylogenesis in Moses and Monotheism to new findings in modern biology and Willi Goetschel relocates Freud in the tradition of works on history that begins with Heine, while Joel Whitebook offers important criticisms of Freud’s main argument about the advance in intellectuality that Freud attributes to Judaism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aViolencexPsychological aspects. 0aViolencexReligious aspects. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Movements / Psychoanalysis.2bisacsh  aAnti-Semitism.  aCultural Memory.  aEgypt.  aFreud.  aHistoriography.  aHolocaust.  aMonotheism.  aMoses.  aMyth.  aReligion.  aTrauma.1 aAssmann, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAssmann, Jan.1 aBernstein, Richard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g